"Krause G.H., Winter K., Krause B., Jahns P., García M., Aranda J., Virgo A.","High-temperature tolerance of a tropical tree, Ficus insipida: Methodological reassessment and climate change considerations",2010,"Functional Plant Biology","37","9",,"890","900",,,10.1071/FP10034,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956299547&partnerID=40&md5=946cf336053ce637211da9994fd9e4e0","Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, Apartado Postal 0843-03092, Panama, Panama; Institute of Plant Biochemistry, Heinrich-Heine University Düsseldorf, Universitätsstraße 1, 40225 Düsseldorf, Germany","Krause, G.H., Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, Apartado Postal 0843-03092, Panama, Panama, Institute of Plant Biochemistry, Heinrich-Heine University Düsseldorf, Universitätsstraße 1, 40225 Düsseldorf, Germany; Winter, K., Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, Apartado Postal 0843-03092, Panama, Panama; Krause, B., Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, Apartado Postal 0843-03092, Panama, Panama; Jahns, P., Institute of Plant Biochemistry, Heinrich-Heine University Düsseldorf, Universitätsstraße 1, 40225 Düsseldorf, Germany; García, M., Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, Apartado Postal 0843-03092, Panama, Panama; Aranda, J., Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, Apartado Postal 0843-03092, Panama, Panama; Virgo, A., Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, Apartado Postal 0843-03092, Panama, Panama","In view of anthropogenic global warming, heat tolerance of a neotropical pioneer tree, Ficus insipida Willd., was determined. Sections of sun leaves from a mature tree and from seedlings cultivated at ambient and elevated temperatures were heated to 4253C. Leaves from a late-successional tree species, Virola sebifera Aubl., were also studied. Widely used chlorophyll a fluorescence methods based on heat-induced rise of initial fluorescence emission, Fo, and decrease in the ratio of variable to maximum fluorescence, Fv/Fm, were reassessed. Fv/F m determined 24h after heat treatment was the fluorescence parameter most suitable to assess the lethal temperature causing permanent tissue damage. Thermo-tolerance was underestimated when Fo and Fv/F m were recorded immediately after the heat treatment. The limit of thermo-tolerance was between 50 and 53C, only a few C above peak leaf temperatures measured in situ. The absence of seasonal changes in thermo-tolerance and only marginal increases in thermo-tolerance of plants grown under elevated temperatures suggest little capacity for further heat acclimation. Heat-stress experiments with intact potted seedlings also revealed irreversible leaf damage at 5153C, but plants survived and developed new leaves during post-culture. © 2010 CSIRO.","biomass; growth; photosynthetic pigments; tropical forest; xanthophyll cycle","After-heat treatment; Anthropogenic global warming; Chlorophyll a fluorescence; Elevated temperature; Fluorescence emission; growth; Heat stress; Heat tolerance; High temperature; In-situ; Leaf damage; Leaf temperature; Lethal temperature; Mature trees; Photosynthetic pigments; Seasonal changes; Sun leaves; Tissue damage; Tree species; Tropical forest; Tropical tree; Xanthophyll cycle; Chlorophyll; Global warming; Heat treatment; Plants (botany); Porphyrins; Tropics; Fluorescence; acclimation; assessment method; biomass; chlorophyll; cultivation; fluorescence; global warming; growth rate; in situ measurement; maturation; seasonal variation; seedling; shrub; succession; temperature effect; tolerance; tropical forest; wild population; Ficus insipida; Virola sebifera",,,,,,"Barnabás, B., Jäger, K., Fehér, A., The effect of drought and heat stress on reproductive processes in cereals (2008) Plant, Cell & Environment, 31, pp. 11-38; Barua, D., Heckathorn, S.A., Coleman, J.S., Variation in heat-shock proteins and photosynthetic thermotolerance among natural populations of Chenopodium album L. from contrasting thermal environments: Implications for plant responses to global 